	<item>
		<title>Suddenly I don&#039;t remember the rules anymore</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2010/11/suddenly-i-dont-remember-the-rules-anymore/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 10 Nov 2010 15:52:40 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=115</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[I think if it weren't for being able to talk to PJ about my life and problems that I would probably go stark raving mad. I always feel so happy and good after talking to him and I think it's because of the release of stress I get just getting to talk to someone who understands.

Rehearsals started for <em>Dirty Rotten Scoundrel</em>s last night. It was a very short rehearsal, being that it was just orientation, and afterwards I was a bit melancholy because I didn't want to go home yet. Nights have been getting harder again lately. Maybe it's the changing seasons and the darkness. Suddenly nights feel especially lonely and my mind wanders. Last night after I got off the phone with PJ I was going through texts and realized I still had a bunch of texts from Paul on my phone. I don't have him as a contact in my phone anymore, but still have the texts. I wondered why I don't delete them, what purpose do they serve? And I thought it's probably the same reason I never deleted Jonathan's profile off of Brain Age. Holding on to some small piece of the past, a record that they were there once, that maybe I was important in someone's life. Maybe I just can't erase people. I know I should learn how.

On the brighter side of life, my boyfriend got my an iPhone! Which is really super awesome and exciting. I also got my front tooth fixed yesterday so now I can start smiling again. Still trying to figure out this career and education thing yet again. I finally started learning Adobe AfterEffects, because you know I needed yet another thing to take up my time and to keep up with (note the sarcasm). But who knows, maybe I'll have as much fun with animation and effects as I did in high school and discover yet another possible career path.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>She says, &quot;Shh...I know, it&#039;s only in my head.&quot;</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2010/11/she-says-shh-i-know-its-only-in-my-head/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 14 Nov 2010 01:00:18 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=122</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Sitting here I suddenly thought, "I wish I had some crayons..." and then immediately thought in reply, "This from the girl who has every other kind of medium imaginable leftover from art school," as my mind took stock of the mass amounts of paint, color pencils, pastels, etc. at my disposal.

I realized that this was a fitting metaphor of my life. No matter what I have I'm never satisfied; there's always something else I want. I'm not actually a very materialistic person, it's not like I just want stuff, or that I care for riches, or always need the best big thing. I think part of the problem is that dreaming is better than the attainment. I could sit down and draw with some color pencils but no, I want crayons. There are at least 15 books in my house that I haven't read but right now in this instant I want to read one that I don't own yet. I could watch 100 different movies in my Netflix queue, movies that I wanted very much to see when they were in theaters, but don't seem as interesting right now as the ones that are in the theater currently.

Really, it's hard to find contentment or satisfaction in anything at all in my current state. When I set my hopes on one thing that I really want then nothing else can keep my focus, and if I can't have it then the things that would normally keep me happy and occupied do neither of those things.

Will I never be satisfied in life? Will there always be something gnawing at me? Was I a gypsy in another life, cursed to be eternally restless? I guess I can't delude myself anymore that I'm okay with being alone all the time. When I think of my happiest times in life, they were always when I had close confidantes and people with whom to share life's treasures. But what do I do? I've tried to make friends here in the Bay Area, and start a new life, but it's all proving much harder than it was in Virginia. Rehearsals start in earnest on Monday and I know I'll feel better once they start, but what happens after this show ends? Or what if it ends up the same as in <em>The Producers</em> when I felt like an outcast and just wanted the show to be over?

I don't know the answers, I never have, but to quote the Counting Crows, "Today was just a day fading into another and that can't be what a life is for."]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>I&#039;d feel so alive if someone like you found me</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2010/11/and-id-feel-so-alive-if-someone-like-you-found-me/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 15 Nov 2010 04:44:52 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=125</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[I think I'm going to take down my portfolio page until I have some time to complete it, because what's there right now is not only such a small portion of my portfolio, but it's really a bad representation of my art as a whole, that I don't want anyone thinking that's all I've got. Part of what actually was holding me back from taking the time to complete it in the first place was wondering if there was even a point in taking the time. Lately I've been worried that I have my ladder against the wrong wallto use a term from <em>The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People</em>and was striving to figure some of that out before expending the effort. I'm considering sticking it out in the field of design and maybe not pursuing video editing. Strangely enough though, I'm trying to get back into motion graphics. There's more of a need for that, as evidenced by Toms telling me he could get me a job in a heartbeat if I was good with AfterEffects. Of course, if he had it his way my next career would be as a breeder *smirk*. I'm just kidding, he's extremely supportive of my career interests and goals, he just wants babies at the same time.

This weekend I thought something had happened to him and it was agonizing; especially the not knowing for sure part. I tried not to let my imagination run away with me, but I've lost so many people throughout my life that I know how very real it is and I always fear the worst. It made me realize how much I don't want to lose him. Not a silly, "How could I ever live without him?" because obviously I can, and would, were something unfortunate to happen to him. It just made me realize that a life with him is what I desire very much, and I'm willing to commit to that now. He frustrates the hell out of me, but that's only because I care about him, which was another small realization.

I read <em>The Scarlet Letter</em> by Nathaniel Hawthorne for the first time. I wish I had read it before 2005, even though I know things are as they should be. After reading it I very much wanted to be Hester Prynne for Halloween, my semi-fictional kindred spirit. Toms is everything I've ever wanted, so much so that it still feels too good to be true, and so surreal. I'm not going to be a fool anymore; I'm going to give in, and not throw away this gift that I have earned and waited for.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>I&#039;m crazy for trying and crazy for crying</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2010/12/im-crazy-for-trying-and-crazy-for-crying/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 04 Dec 2010 05:44:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=137</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Someday I want to know what it feels like to have someone be crazy about me, or does that really only happen in the movies? I know things are always better in the books and in the movies, but can't it be possible for someone to adore me? I've adored other people but never had it returned.

Is it really just me? I used to think I was quirky and abnormal but the more I see of the world the more I realize that I'm really not that unique. Is that it? I'm not special enough for anyone to be crazy about? I hide away in my little world learning and studying everything but how to interact with other human beings. No...actually I even study that sometimes, but can never find living beings to test out my newfound knowledge on. "Not enough field research," that's what Asa used to tell me.

I guess deep down I'm just like everyone else. I want to be understood and I want to be loved. I want someone to think about me all the time, to yearn for me, and to not be able to get enough of me, and I'm not talking physical passion, though that would be nice too. People have lusted after me before, but no ones ever been crazy about me as a person. I want someone to be delighted in all the new things they learn about me, to smile with the pure joy of hanging out with me, to be enthusiastic about all the possibilities of life that can only be achieved through the synergy of our two beings.

And that's all idealistic bullshit, I know.

Maybe I just want someone who'll return my calls. But I always want too much.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Ode to my birthday</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2010/12/ode-to-my-birthday/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 06 Dec 2010 21:05:04 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=141</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[I Dreamed a Dream from Les Misrables

There was a time when men were kind,
And their voices were soft,
And their words inviting.
There was a time when love was blind,
And the world was a song,
And the song was exciting.
There was a time when it all went wrong...

I dreamed a dream in time gone by,
When hope was high and life worth living.
I dreamed that love would never die,
I dreamed that God would be forgiving.
Then I was young and unafraid,
And dreams were made and used and wasted.
There was no ransom to be paid,
No song unsung, no wine, untasted.

But the tigers come at night,
With their voices soft as thunder,
As they tear your hope apart,
And they turn your dream to shame.

He slept a summer by my side,
He filled my days with endless wonder...
He took my childhood in his stride,
But he was gone when autumn came!

And still I dream he'll come to me,
That we will live the years together,
But there are dreams that cannot be,
And there are storms we cannot weather!

I had a dream my life would be
So different from this hell I'm living,
So different now from what it seemed...
Now life has killed the dream I dreamed...]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>All I want for Christmas is you</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2010/12/all-i-want-for-christmas-is-you/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 24 Dec 2010 06:19:55 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=149</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[It's hard to plan out my work schedule over the next few months with so much of my life up in the air right now. It's also nearing the time that I will need to start applying to new jobs. I've decided that I'm going to look for a high-paying job, regardless of whether it's in my career field or not, because the sooner I get out the debt, the sooner I can do all the things that I really want to do; which includes even more education.

There are some things I'm so excited about right now, and others that are dragging me down, which balances out into a very neutral place. Since I tend to rant on here more than rave, let's focus on all the good things.
	<li>I have two new books to read. <em>Geek Love</em> by Katherine Dunn and <em>What is the What</em> by Dave Eggers.</li>
	<li>I have a new instructional piano book to further my skill.</li>
	<li>I have eggnog to drink AND eggnog cookies!</li>
	<li>I'm going to be getting the professional massage that I've been wanting since time began.</li>
	<li>I saw The Nutcracker performed by the San Francisco Ballet!!</li>
	<li>I have a new RPG to play for the first time in years. ^_^</li>
	<li>I actually have something to do for New Year's Eve this year! (though truth be told I'm worried about getting lonely, but I guess I'd be lonely if I was at home too, so might as well be doing something, right?)</li>
	<li>I'm actually getting caught up on my to-do list at work, which is great with Winter Games right around the corner.</li>

I really hope I get some specific things cleared up before the end of the year. I don't like operating on confusion and uncertainty.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>But there&#039;s no color I can have on Earth that won&#039;t finally fade</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2010/12/but-theres-no-color-i-can-have-on-earth-that-wont-finally-fade/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 28 Dec 2010 16:16:28 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=153</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Earlier this year I posted a Facebook status about how I realized that the source of my discontent was that on any given day I felt like I should be doing something extraordinary. A few people laughed and said, "Didn't you learn anything from Pippin?" For those of you who are unfamiliar with the musical, here is a summary:

<blockquote>Once upon a time, the young prince Pippin longed to discover the secret of true happiness and fulfillment. He sought it in the glories of the battlefield, the temptations of the flesh and the intrigues of political power (after disposing of his father King Charlemagne the Great). In the end, he found it in the simple pleasures of home and family. </blockquote>

He whines through the whole musical about needing to find his corner of the sky, and sings about how he has to be extraordinary. Obviously it parallels to my own journey but I guess the answer was no, I didn't learn anything from Pippin. The finale of the show came on while I was working yesterday and upon truly listening to it for the first time in a while it dawned on me that I had my own Pippin-esque revelation within the last couple months that ended in the same result. My priorities have shifted. Performing used to be my entire life. I once said that life is all about performing in a show and everything else is just filler. I've been wearing my theatre masks on my wedding finger for almost 3 years to show my devotion, knowing that I'd never love a man or anything else as much as I did theatre. I've found myself caring less and less about performing these last couple months and I wasn't sure why. These days I sit in rehearsal and while I enjoy singing and dancing, I sit there wondering why I don't feel that spark or devotion anymore; the feeling that this is exactly where I'm supposed to be.

It's because I realized the same thing that Pippin did. I still love theatre but there's something I want more now, but instead of the realization bringing contentment to my life, it makes me kind of sad; because obtaining what I truly want now, is far more difficult than being cast as the lead in a show. No one's ever wanted to cast me as a lead in their life. I always fail the auditions. So what do you do?

Maybe I'll do as the great Jane Austen did and become a writer. It's too bad I suck at making stories up. Asides, I'm tired of living vicariously through fictional characters, or otherwise.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>&quot;Art is never finished, only abandoned.&quot;</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/02/art-is-never-finished-only-abandoned/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 20 Feb 2011 20:14:36 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/?p=92</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[After way too long of picking at it, I think I'm willing to let it go and say that my resume is complete for now. I've pretty much been working on it nonstop, and I'm sure that most people that look at it would ask, "Why did that take you over 20 hours to do?" but I think other artsy perfectionists would understand...hopefully. Now, if I could just get the new site more completed, I'll be on a great roll! The only problem is being so swamped at my official job right now, so we'll see what happens.

Those of you interested in actually looking at it can find it <a href="http://theamysloan.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/sloan_resume.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>. I'm not sure where I'm putting in on this site yet.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Life starts anew</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/02/life-starts-anew/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 27 Feb 2011 01:53:57 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/?p=121</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[It's recently become very clear to me that the biggest immediate goal in my life right now is to get hired by a fun tech startup in the city. The search is both exciting and nerve-wrecking, much akin to dating. "Oh my gosh, what if no one wants me?" But like love, I'm sure that when it does fit for both the company and me, it will be glorious.

So many exciting things on the horizon and I've got a smile on my face!]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Ready, steady, go!</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/03/ready-steady-go/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 28 Mar 2011 00:06:32 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/?p=140</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[A lot has been going on over the last month. I just got back from a 3 week business trip to Colorado for the <a href="http://www.shiningstarsfoundation.org/our-programs/aspen-winter-games/">Aspen Winter Games</a>. It was once again a big success, and my big project, as usual, was creating the slideshow for the banquet. Every year I am faced with the challenge of creating it on a time crunch with limited resources, but every year I get countless compliments on it, so I suppose I must be doing something right. Once I finish compressing the video I will be posting it online if anyone is interested in it. Past years can be found <a href="http://www.shiningstarsfoundation.org/media/winter-games-slideshows/">here</a>. One thing that really stood out to me was how much I really enjoyed getting a chance to work with video again. It made me long to pursue a career in video editing again, though I know it's not likely or practical. However, this is the first year that I was chosen to edit the entire Winter Games souvenir video that will be sent to all the kids, families, and volunteers, and I'm really excited about the project.

Speaking of video projects, I <em>finally</em> added a video section to my portfolio on here. It doesn't have everything I want there yet, but it's a good start. I've been applying to a lot of jobs at startups, but so far haven't had much luck. I'm leaning towards becoming specialized in something that's popular right now to give myself an advantage but as usual cannot figure out exactly what I want to do the most. I was thinking about getting into UI design, but the passion just isn't there so far; maybe when I start getting into it more that will change. I don't know why all the things that I'm interested in the most aren't practical; I suppose it's part of the curse of being interested in too many things at once. Now that I'm back in town though I've hit the ground running and am really motivated to get a lot of things rolling. I've got some new business cards, I'm going to get out there and network, continue my education here at home for newer and better things, and I'm still apartment hunting in the city, though without a roommate now. Good things are on the horizon!]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Someday I&#039;ll fly, someday I&#039;ll soar</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/03/someday-ill-fly-someday-ill-soar/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 30 Mar 2011 18:50:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/?p=142</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[For those who may have not seen the retweet, here is a <a href="http://www.facebook.com/video/video.php?v=208574029169408&oid=152315315683&comments">link to the video</a> I made for the 2011 Aspen Winter Games Awards Ceremony. It's kind of a wrap-up of the week, and therefore it gets made very quickly at the end, so I'm never fully satisfied with it, but other people are, so maybe I'm just too hard on myself.

I'm starting to think that I'm letting fear prevent me from pursuing the things that I really want to pursue. I have some good reasons for applying for office jobs at tech startups, but I realized yesterday that more than anything that's what's "easy" and comfortable for me. I'm going to work harder to attempt to do the artsy things I really want to do. I just never seem to know where to start. On the bright side I least I have the artsy jobs I get on the side from my long-term loyal clients. I really am looking forward to editing the souvenir video for Winter Games. I'll be getting a start on that soon :-)]]></content:encoded>

		<title></title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/04/you-must-not-for-one-instant-give-up-the-effort/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 24 Apr 2011 17:37:39 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/04/you-must-not-for-one-instant-give-up-the-effort/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>You must not for one instant give up the effort to build new lives for yourselves. Creativity means to push open the heavy, groaning doorway to life. This is not an easy struggle. Indeed, it may be the most difficult task in the world, for opening the door to your own life is, in the end, more difficult than opening the doors to the mysteries of the universe.</blockquote>

<div class='attribution'>Daisaku Ikeda</div>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>If you want better things I want you to have them</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/01/if-you-want-better-things-i-want-you-to-have-them/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 07 Jan 2011 21:22:21 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=155</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[It is now been a week since I had my epiphany on New Year's Eve while zoning out during the Pomplamoose set at the Dresden Dolls concert, and it's been the first week in a very long time that I've consistently felt this good about myself and my life. Obviously the Care Bears were on to something! I bought myself an iPhone and am absolutely in love with it. I've been tracking my mood since the beginning of the year with an app.

The show opens in two weeks and I'm looking forward to having my weeknights off again, if only to get some more reading time in; I'm in book heaven at the moment with so many options to choose from. My traveling starts again soon, well the day after the show closes, but then after March I'm released from my contract and am free to pursue new adventures. It's both scary and exciting of course, but I'm sure whatever happens will be good and beneficial to my life.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>There&#039;s a serious single man drought</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/01/theres-a-serious-single-man-drought/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 15 Jan 2011 20:07:07 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/blog/?p=158</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[I'm starting to realize that the older I get, the less likely it is that I will find someone worthwhile to share my life with, because they will already be taken by other people. I wish I could go back to not caring about relationships or wanting one, but I've realized how much more rewarding and amazing life can be with one. I don't want to have a child alone anymore; I want to share that experience with someone else. Everyone always says don't settle, and I haven't since my first relationship, but that means I may be alone forever. Maybe it's less important to find someone I can love, than it is to find someone who'll love me. I suppose I should start by leaving my house, right? /smirk

I am going to start applying for new jobs in just another month and I've been hard at work updating my resumes, and preparing for that time. I've really got my hopes up to find an awesome new job, hopefully related to technology or art in some capacity, and with good benefits. I don't think I have my sights set too high because there's really a lot of that in this area. I think a lot of things will fall into place after that. If all goes well I'll move right into the city, I'll be making friends at work, and who knows, maybe someone will ask me on a date in real life (for the first time ever). It could happen!

Working on the Disney World plans. Unfortunately I don't think I'm going to be able to find availability for when my cousin goes, which means I'll be going alone but that's okay because I have a friend who works there! :-) I'm really excited about it, and wish I could take the vacation sooner.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title></title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/sometimes-i-find-myself-wondering-how-different-my/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 19 May 2011 17:37:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/sometimes-i-find-myself-wondering-how-different-my/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sBt2ycLrC6Q
<p>Sometimes I find myself wondering how different my life would be today if I hadn&#8217;t had such a life altering experience when I was 20 years old. My perspective changed, my goals changed, everything changed.</p>
<p>Who would I be today? Where would I have gone? Would I still feel as broken, perpetually trying to re-obtain what was taken from me? Did it make me a stronger person, or a better person? Was there any good that came from it? I&#8217;m still asking myself these questions all these years later. I get more numb to it as the years go on but I find that it still steers my life.</p>
<p>It made me afraid to give in last fall, when someone offered me exactly what I wanted, but didn&#8217;t know it yet. Now all I want is that chance again, but it&#8217;s no longer there. So many missed opportunities. So many &#8220;What if&#8217;s?&#8221;</p>
<p>And I overanalyze it all. I torture myself. I am my own worst enemy.</p><div class="attribution">(<span>Source:</span> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/">http://www.youtube.com/</a>)</div>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>What TV show do you wish was still on the air?</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/what-tv-show-do-you-wish-was-still-on-the-air/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 16 May 2011 21:20:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/what-tv-show-do-you-wish-was-still-on-the-air/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><p class="formspringmeAnswer">Being that I don&#8217;t watch television for the most part, it&#8217;s pretty easy to choose from the limited shows I know. All the ones that I like had some pretty good runs that ended when they should have. I think the only one I want a little bit more of is Firefly. Maybe just 1 or 2 seasons. I&#8217;m sure it would get bad eventually.</p>

<p class="formspringmeFooter">
    <a href="http://www.formspring.me/amsloan?utm_medium=social&amp;utm_source=tumblr&amp;utm_campaign=shareanswer" target="_blank">What would you like to know?</a>
</p></p>]]></content:encoded>

<p>&#8220;Jobs are not big enough for people. You ask most people who they are, they define themselves by their jobs. I&#8217;m a doctor, I&#8217;m a radio announcer, I&#8217;m a carpenter. If someone asks <em>me</em>, I say &#8216;I&#8217;m Amanda McKenny, and at certain points in time, I do things for a living.&#8221;</p><div class="attribution">(<span>Source:</span> <a href="http://www.facebook.com/">http://www.facebook.com/</a>)</div>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Life upon the wicked stage...</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/life-upon-the-wicked-stage/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 07 May 2011 00:30:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/life-upon-the-wicked-stage/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I&#8217;ve spent my entire adult life living out experiences on stage instead of off it, and that used to be enough for me.</p>
<p>I got a small taste of the beauty of a real relationship and found myself no longer content to play pretend on stage. I decided that I wanted a life outside of the theatre, that I wanted more things, real things; that I wanted to really live my life out there in the world instead of living other people&#8217;s lives on stage. I had a Pippin-esque revelation, I suppose.</p>
<p>But now months later I&#8217;m starting to remember why theatre held such an allure in the first place. You get to experience all the life you might never get to live otherwise, and maybe it isn&#8217;t real, but it&#8217;s something. On stage I&#8217;ve been a lawyer, a heroine, a wife, a violinist, a crazy playwright, a follies girl, a waitress, a maid, even a bird, and much more. On stage I&#8217;ve had husbands and offstage I haven&#8217;t had an official boyfriend in 9 years. I suppose the lifespan of a theatre show made me accustomed to the short flings you&#8217;d experience in and around them. &#8220;What happens at the theatre stays at the theatre,&#8221; and that&#8217;s the problem, isn&#8217;t it? You&#8217;re still alone at the end of the day. I used to be okay with that, the life I was living in the shows, but now&#8230;I don&#8217;t know what I want.</p>
<p>I guess after 9 years of being a mistress I wanted something to call my own. I wanted to know what it feels like to be someone&#8217;s girlfriend. I want to be adored and cherished, to have someone to makes plans with and go out and about with; someone I could hold hands with in public and fall asleep next to at night. I thought, after all this time, that I deserve it, right?</p>
<p>But maybe the fictions on stage have made me believe they can exist elsewhere and they really can&#8217;t. Maybe a stage wife is all I will ever be, and maybe there isn&#8217;t anything wrong with that. On January 1st of this year I removed the theatre masks ring that I had worn on my wedding finger for 3 years. I was ready to &#8220;break up&#8221; with theatre and give my devotion to a man instead, when I once thought I would never love a man as much as I did theatre. I tucked it away in a drawer and haven&#8217;t pulled it back out since. It bothered that man that I said I would never get married and that I wore that ring on my finger. Then I find out that the brief taste of something real wasn&#8217;t actually real anyway. It was all fake, and the person was just playing pretend, except I bought into it because I didn&#8217;t think it was scripted.</p>
<p>So again, I find myself being attracted back to a stage where I can experience all the things that I might never experience in real life. I feel like apologizing to theatre for forsaking it, thinking that I could find satisfaction elsewhere. I suppose I&#8217;m not ready to throw the towel in on real life yet and make my return to the stage, but it is getting tempting. While I would love to know what it feels like to be someone&#8217;s girlfriend, I&#8217;m still picky and won&#8217;t settle on just anyone, and I think the likeliness of someone I&#8217;m interested in actually liking me back is nonexistent.</p>
<p>So can you blame me for wanting to spend time in a place where men get to pretend to be in love with me for a couple hours each night? Who cares if they&#8217;re gay 1/2 the time, right? ;-) I haven&#8217;t been a mother yet on stage though, and that is something I absolutely long for.</p>
<p><img src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lkstpk2kA11qcdyar.jpg" /></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Why do we chase after people who don&#039;t love us back? </title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/why-do-we-chase-after-people-who-dont-love-us-back/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 05 May 2011 23:33:42 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/why-do-we-chase-after-people-who-dont-love-us-back/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><p class="formspringmeAnswer">If I knew the answer to that my life would sure be a lot easier.<br /><br />
That being said, I think it can be for different reasons with different people, but for me it&#8217;s never had anything to do with the &#8220;thrill of the chase&#8221; or wanting something just because you can&#8217;t have it. In the most recent case of this in my life, someone was head over heels for me but I need time to get to know someone before I become emotionally attached. So when I did finally fall in love with them, they suddenly decided they no longer wanted me, and I then spent months chasing after them and loving them because I couldn&#8217;t rid myself of the idea in my head of when they did actually adore and want me.<br /><br />
I think a lot of times it&#8217;s that we think they just don&#8217;t realize how great we are, and that if they would just give us a chance they&#8217;d be happy. The problem is that no one can really control the chemicals that make them feel the way they do, so just as you think you can&#8217;t help loving them, they can&#8217;t help the fact that they don&#8217;t love you.<br /><br />
Sometimes it&#8217;s the dirty trick that nature plays on us to get us to reproduce. The pheromones given off by another person can make us feel attraction, because nature thinks we&#8217;d be a compatible match for mating.<br /><br />
There are no easy answers. Most of us do it. Most of us know we&#8217;re being idiots, but we still chase and try to force our love on those that don&#8217;t want it.<br /><br />
I probably shouldn&#8217;t be answering this question when I&#8217;m feeling particularly jaded and bitter about relationships. After repeatedly being in love with people who don&#8217;t love me back, I obviously don&#8217;t have the answers.<br /><br />
Maybe we&#8217;re all just masochists.</p>

<p class="formspringmeFooter">
    <a href="http://www.formspring.me/amsloan?utm_medium=social&amp;utm_source=tumblr&amp;utm_campaign=shareanswer" target="_blank">What would you like to know?</a>
</p></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Would you rather be the best player on a losing team or the worst player on a winning team?</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/would-you-rather-be-the-best-player-on-a-losing-team-or/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 05 May 2011 07:00:35 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/would-you-rather-be-the-best-player-on-a-losing-team-or/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><p class="formspringmeAnswer">Thinking of my experience in theatre, I&#8217;d definitely rather be the worst player on a winning team. I don&#8217;t need other people to be bad to make me feel good about myself. I would much rather learn and improve from the greatness around me. Also when you&#8217;re around a great team it motivates and inspires you to be better. When you&#8217;re stuck as the best person around a &#8220;losing team&#8221; it really just ends up bringing you down and making you feel defeated in the end.</p>

<p class="formspringmeFooter">
    <a href="http://www.formspring.me/amsloan?utm_medium=social&amp;utm_source=tumblr&amp;utm_campaign=shareanswer" target="_blank">What would you like to know?</a>
</p></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>That elusive ingredient</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/that-elusive-ingredient/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 03 May 2011 11:49:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/that-elusive-ingredient/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Ive reached a point in my life where I know very much want I want but I am struggling to find and obtain it. Its frustrating and sometimes makes me start to despair. I am just hoping that once I do get my hands on it that it really does make life just that much better. Heres to hoping and continuing the pursuit.</p>
<p><strong>Update</strong>: It&#8217;s occurred to me that posting things in the middle of the night is almost like drunk posting. This morning I was closing apps on my iPhone and saw that Tumblr had been open and had a moment of panic wondering what I posted.</p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Not Failure, but Low Aim is Sin</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/not-failure-but-low-aim-is-sin/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 27 May 2011 16:11:47 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/?p=173</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://www.swiss-miss.com/2011/05/not-failure-but-low-aim-is-sin.html">swissmiss | Not Failure, but Low Aim is Sin</a>.

I always feel better about my life when I have goals that I'm working towards, and when I am dreaming of good things, however unrealistic. Sometimes I start to despair, and sometimes I think of just giving up because it's never going to happen anyway, but then I think to myself, <strong>"Try harder."</strong>]]></content:encoded>

		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[gallery]
<p>I&#8217;ve passed through Winnemucca on the trip back and forth from CA to ID more times in my life than I could ever count, but I can still remember being an 8 year old and sitting on a mattress in a van with my sister in that parking lot the very first time, when we were taken from CA to start different lives. (Taken with <a href="http://instagr.am" target="_blank">Instagram</a> at Winners Hotel Casino)</p>]]></content:encoded>

		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/so-avoid-using-the-word-very-because-its-lazy/</link>

		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/05/so-avoid-using-the-word-very-because-its-lazy/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>So avoid using the word very because its lazy. A man is not very tired, he is exhausted. Dont use very sad, use morose. Language was invented for one reason, boys - to woo women - and, in that endeavor, laziness will not do.</blockquote>

<div class='attribution'>Dead Poets Society (1989)</div>]]></content:encoded>

		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>

		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>Would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?<br />
That depends a good deal on where you want to get to, said the Cat.<br />
I dont much care where said Alice.<br />
Then it doesnt matter which way you go, said the Cat.<br />
so long as I get SOMEWHERE, Alice added as an explanation.<br />
Oh, youre sure to do that, said the Cat, if you only walk long enough.</blockquote>

<div class='attribution'>Alices Adventures in Wonderland by Lewis Carroll, Chapter 6</div>]]></content:encoded>

		<title></title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/06/babies-do-not-need-toys-i-am-endlessly/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 28 Jun 2011 15:21:30 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/06/babies-do-not-need-toys-i-am-endlessly/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[http://vimeo.com/25700271
<p>Babies do not need toys.</p>
<p>I am endlessly fascinated when watching babies explore and figure out the world. I am also quite entertained by the fact that they&#8217;d rather play with something simple than any of the fancy toys we tend to shower them with. My shoes kept my 14 month old nephew occupied for about 30 minutes.</p><div class="attribution">(<span>Source:</span> <a href="http://vimeo.com/">http://vimeo.com/</a>)</div>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>&quot;A good design won&#039;t please everyone.&quot;</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/07/a-good-design-wont-please-everyone/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 28 Jul 2011 01:40:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/?p=178</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://www.dkeithrobinson.com/features/entry/consensus_is_for_losers/" title="Consensus is for Losers" target="_blank">Consensus is for Losers</a>

This is a great blog entry from Keith Robinson that states many things that I have tried to hammer into the heads of people I have worked with on designs.
<blockquote>"You simply cannot have a strong design if you have to please too many people."</blockquote>

The funny thing is that there seems to be a consensus (haha) among designers that this is the case, so my question is: why are we still having to fight people on this? Also, even worse than design committees are non-designers thinking they know best, which results in this: <a href="http://theoatmeal.com/comics/design_hell" target="_blank">How a Web Design Goes Straight to Hell</a>. The latter subject being what I deal with the most. I know we've all been there, and I'm probably preaching to the choir, but I sometimes think, "Why do I even bother?" So often I end up in frustration because of watching people argue back and forth about how I should design something, and wondering why they hired me in the first place when they act like they're the experts and I know nothing. However, I guess I should take Keith's advice, "Argue with your clients if you feel strongly theyre not doing what is in their best interests."]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>The US budget is like a 1st grader playing Oregon Trail. Spend all the money on ammunition so you can shoot at stuff, then wonder why your wagon is falling apart and everyone is dying of dysentery.</blockquote>

	<item>
		<title>Where do we go from here?</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/12/where-do-we-go-from-here/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 02 Dec 2011 03:50:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/12/where-do-we-go-from-here/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Right now I&#8217;m job hunting, apartment hunting, and dealing with the robbery and insurance claims, and yet I haven&#8217;t gone off the deep end yet, and feel like somehow it&#8217;s all going to work out.</p>
<p>I thank Jesse for a lot of that, who has been a great source of comfort and support. It&#8217;s the first time in my life I&#8217;ve felt like I&#8217;ve had a real partner in life.</p>
<p>I feel pretty discouraged about the jobs though, as I don&#8217;t see why it will be any better than the previous 8 months that I was looking. I just don&#8217;t feel like I fit in anywhere. Thousands of jobs are posted on dice.com for the bay area, every day, and I&#8217;m not qualified for any of them.And I feel even less prepared than before for any new design pursuits, after losing all my files, work, and pretty resume. Obviously you never know what will happen if you don&#8217;t keep trying, so I do, but how long does it take until you realize you must just be a complete failure?</p>
<p>I started school again this summer because so many jobs won&#8217;t hire you unless you have a degree, and after making it most of the way through the semester I had to drop one of my classes, that I had an A in, just because it was getting harder and harder to find the time with how busy I was at work. Now I&#8217;m not working, and am still no closer to a degree, and realistically won&#8217;t be for at least another 3 years. How does one make a living in that time?</p>
<p>I keep vowing to obtain the skills to be a developer, a career path in which there is lots of work, but I can never muster the enthusiasm to follow through. I think I&#8217;m going to have to tell myself, &#8220;You&#8217;ll do it, or you&#8217;ll starve.&#8221; That certainly is a wake up call.</p>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[gallery]
<p><a class="tumblr_blog" href="http://bikebasketpies.tumblr.com/post/12942114198/the-recipe-booklet-is-finally-being-released-bike" target="_blank">bikebasketpies</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The recipe booklet is finally being released! <em>Bike Basket Pies: How to Make Handheld Pies for Bicycle Delivery</em> includes 14 seasonal pie recipes and illustrations by <a href="http://pscomics.com" target="_blank">Minty Lewis</a>.</p>
<p>Theres a release party at Pot + Pantry on Tuesday, November 29th - its BYOPie (not required, of course), and therell be champagne (and pie!).</p>
<p><a href="http://www.facebook.com/events/242297809165440/" target="_blank">facebook invite</a>and <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/viewform?hl=en_US&amp;formkey=dE1MYWdIYnJfNUNNWVVPcE5hdk5uVmc6MQ#gid=0" target="_blank">RSVP</a></p>

	<item>
		<title></title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/10/heres-to-the-crazy-ones-the-misfits-the-rebels/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 06 Oct 2011 05:38:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/10/heres-to-the-crazy-ones-the-misfits-the-rebels/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>Heres to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. Theyre not fond of rules. And they have no respect for the status quo. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you cant do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the people who are crazy enough to think they can change the world, are the ones who do.</blockquote>

<div class='attribution'>Apple Inc. (via <a href="http://also.unraveled.com/" target="_blank">joshuakaufman</a>)</div>]]></content:encoded>

		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>Date a girl who reads. Date a girl who spends her money on books instead of clothes. She has problems with closet space because she has too many books. Date a girl who has a list of books she wants to read, who has had a library card since she was twelve.</blockquote>

<div class='attribution'><a href="http://nonamerah.wordpress.com/2011/10/03/869/?refid=12" target="_blank">A Girl You Should Date</a>via <a href="http://twitter.com/#!/brainpicker/status/153500738289541122" target="_blank">@brainpicker</a> (via <a href="http://bookshelfporn.com/" class="tumblr_blog" target="_blank">bookshelfporn</a>)</div>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>I Work For The Internet</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2011/12/i-work-for-the-internet/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 13 Dec 2011 18:14:55 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2011/12/i-work-for-the-internet/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href='http://iworkfortheinternet.org/'>I Work For The Internet</a><div class="link_description"><p><a href="http://mydrunkkitchen.tumblr.com/post/14171157821/i-work-for-the-internet" class="tumblr_blog" target="_blank">mydrunkkitchen</a>:</p>

<blockquote><p><b>Fight for the Future</b></p>

<p>We work for the Internet. We know first-hand that the Internet powers the American dream. American innovators have built the worlds most popular sites, selling products and services to every corner of the globe, creating high-paying jobs from Maine to Hawaii. If Congress passes the Stop Online Piracy Act, Americas most promising engine of future jobs and opportunity will be put at risk. Dont stop us now  were just getting started! Tell the world you work for the Internet.</p></blockquote></div>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Stuck between the analog and the digital</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2012/03/stuck-between-the-analog-and-the-digital/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 24 Mar 2012 18:52:43 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/?p=207</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[One of the things that I value in the workplace is efficiency. At every company I've worked for I've delighted in discovering and implementing more efficient methods of carrying out tasks. Being that I'm often the most tech savvy person at a lot of the companies I've worked for, I've strived to help them adopt newer technologies and methods of running more efficiently, whenever I'm in a position to do so. The managing teams are often very enthusiastic about this, sometimes I'm even part of the managing team, but I've sometimes found it very hard to get employees to accept and adopt newer technologies and/or newer methods. This serves as a great frustration for me; when I've spent a lot of time and effort trying to make things better for other people and they just dismiss it.

Some might say, "Well everyone has a different way of doing things and the methods you institute may not work best for everyone," and that is true, but many of the technologies I have shown people are an undeniable asset. For example, the person who needs to re-size 100 pictures in Photoshop, in order to upload them somewhere on the internet (which they most likely even know how to do because I taught them), and says that it'll take forever. I personally just use automation for this task, but many people do not know how to do this. So I provide them with some easy free software that's sole purpose is to do this very task for them. You just give it the pictures and it spits them back out at the setting you ask for, but then they just end up not using it and either continue to complain that the task will take forever, or they just neglect to do the task at all. This type of example is an issue I've run into a lot. I've also run into the issue of people flat out not caring about being more efficient with their work, or having easier ways to accomplish tasks. As long as they are getting their paycheck they're fine with the status quo; they're fine with tasks being harder than they have to be.<!--more-->

On the other hand I've also ran into people who have been too ambitious, when I've provided them with tools that make things easy for them; this can also be disastrous. I'm all for people learning new skills and trying to do more, but the key word here is <em>learning</em> and not just assuming that you know how to do something. The example in this case is designing and setting up a CMS or cookie cutter website for someone. You design and set up an entire website and get it running, and then give them the ability to just edit text in the body whenever they need to, or add images to the body, etc. This all works fine for a while, but then they decide they want to do different things; they want to change the design, or start using different fonts etc, but instead of coming to you and asking for you to implement new designs or features, they try to do it themselves, and all of a sudden a professional working website starts looking like a geocities site from the 90's. Very similar in fact, to what <a title="How a Web Design Goes Straight to Hell" href="http://theoatmeal.com/comics/design_hell" target="_blank">this comic</a> illustrates. Now I'm not just talking about them changing some colors, or something minor, but things like interfering with the information architecture of the site, or copying and pasting cursive fonts from a word document into the text editor so that they'll have "pretty" text on the site, not realizing that the typeface is not only unreadable, but is not a standard font on everyone's computer so it may look pretty on <strong>their</strong> computer, but everyone else can't even <strong>see</strong> the font they were trying to display. If you know nothing about making a website, then the internet is a wealth of knowledge with thousands of articles of information on very basic principles of design and building websites that can be read to try and figure things out, so there is no excuse for this. In the hands of people who just assume they know what they're doing, however, these "easy" tools provided to them can create a monster.

I realize that I'm preaching to the choir with most of the people who read this blog, but it's something that has driven me increasingly nuts over the yearsall my hard work gone to waste, all the people who will continue to complain, or continue to live in the past with outdated technology. I know I need to stop caring, but the issue is that it makes me want to stop trying to help people. If people aren't going to trust my expertise, or try to learn and adapt, then I don't want to waste my time. I guess that I'm getting to the breaking point, and that's very sad for me because this "thing" that I've been very good at for many years has combined both my intense urge to help people, and my love of technology.

I am always humbled by how much I don't know, and it's part of what drives me to continue learning more constantly. I'm starting to wonder though, what's the use of all that knowledge if I can't put it to work? What good is anything if it's never used? Should I continue to spend half my time learning things that may never get used, or may never be lucrative? Or should I spend that time doing things I enjoy more, like reading books for pleasure, or playing video games? Up until now a great portion of my knowledge has only been useful in helping people in the ways mentioned above: fixing people computers, figuring out the little things that they cannot, providing resources and information to make work easier, showing them how to be more independent, and teaching them to use more tools. So if I don't do that anymore then what's the use of my knowledge?

You often hear of starving artists, but I've been a starving tech-geek for a long time. Jack of all trades, master of none, that's me. I'd prefer to be thought of more as a polymath, but such people are not valued by the workforce anymore anyway. Employers want specialists, and yet I've reached a point where I'm afraid to "waste" my time becoming an expert in one particular field when there's no guarantee of it being lucrative. I spent years trying to specialize in fields that have become obsolete, or in fields that just didn't suit me. At the end of the day I have amassed lots of knowledge, but at the end of the day I'm still just a starving tech-geek.

What does a tech-geek do when they no longer want to play ball with the non-technical people, yet are incapable of being embraced by the rest of the tech community at large?]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title></title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2012/03/for-a-while-the-excitement-and-passion-had-been/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 01 Mar 2012 01:39:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2012/03/for-a-while-the-excitement-and-passion-had-been/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[gallery]
<p>For a while the excitement and passion had been stolen from me, but these last few weeks I&#8217;ve felt it increasingly coming back. People finally stopped asking me, &#8220;Are you doing any shows right now?&#8221; so I no longer had to deal with the awkwardness of saying such foreign words for me: &#8220;No. I haven&#8217;t been auditioning for anything; I&#8217;ve got other things going on right now,&#8221; and seeing the look of concern from those that know that theatre always took precedence.</p>
<p>Today I watched a dvd of the last show that I did and was disturbed seeing how skinny I had gotten, how each weekend my costumes were falling off me more and more, remembering how every night was a struggle as I sat onstage behind the set trying not to cry as I listened to the lead sing &#8220;Nothing is too wonderful to be true,&#8221; and how I had wasted away because of what was going on in my life at the time; the person who I felt had help rob me of my passion and left me with a gaping hole in my life that theatre had always filled before.</p>
<p>After 3 years of never removing it (except while on stage), I took this ring off my wedding finger and tucked it away, mourning the loss of what I had felt my entire life, wondering why it was gone, and angry towards the person that was wreaking havoc in my life. In these past few months I&#8217;ve occasionally thought, &#8220;Maybe I&#8217;ll start auditioning again,&#8221; but could never bring myself to do it. That longing, that need, was still missing, and kept me frozen on the couch.</p>
<p>Now, over a year later, I feel that fire returning. The joy of thinking about doing a show, the yearning, the endless research, and the smiles and happiness that comes from just thinking about it all the time and preparing. The enthusiasm and motivation to put in the work necessary to get back in the saddle. I don&#8217;t think I realized how much I missed that feeling until it started to return. And so now I feel worthy once more of wearing this ring, and am surprised at how comforting and familiar it feels on my finger.  Maybe it&#8217;s a return to myself, maybe it&#8217;s the start of something new. Either way I can&#8217;t wait to dust off the piano and my character shoes, and get back on stage again.</p>]]></content:encoded>

		<title></title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2012/02/i-dont-know-if-youve-ever-felt-like-that-that/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 17 Feb 2012 19:49:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2012/02/i-dont-know-if-youve-ever-felt-like-that-that/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>I dont know if youve ever felt like that. That you wanted to sleep for a thousand years. Or just not exist. Or just not be aware that you do exist. Or something like that. I think wanting that is very morbid, but I want it when I get like this. Thats why Im trying not to think. I just want it all to stop spinning.</blockquote>

<div class='attribution'>Stephen Chbosky, The Perks of Being a Wallflower</div>]]></content:encoded>

		<title></title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2012/02/in-this-dirty-minded-world-you-are-either/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 13 Feb 2012 03:20:53 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2012/02/in-this-dirty-minded-world-you-are-either/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>In this dirty minded world you are either somebody&#8217;s wife or somebody&#8217;s whoreor fast on your way to becoming one or the other. I wanted a job and I wanted to live alone. That made me a sexual suspect. Then I wanted a baby, but I didn&#8217;t want to have to share my body or my life to have one. That made me a sexual suspect too.</blockquote>

<div class='attribution'>The World According to Garp by John Irving</div>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>I&#039;m Alive</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2012/08/im-alive/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 11 Aug 2012 00:52:57 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/?p=229</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Talk about extreme neglect of my website. I never even finished my "year in review" that I do at the end of every year. Trying to do it as a blog this year instead of an electronic newsletter made it too long and overwhelming until I abandoned it completely. I've hardly been online these past few months, and while the reasons are mostly happy ones, I do wish I had more time for my side projects, such as this website. For a while I was trying to keep this blog less personal and more about things other people might be interested in, but I suppose that's what twitter is for and in the end this is my space to do with it what I will. As such, I'm tempted to go back to talking about what's going on in my life, there for whomever might be interested in knowing. I'm not doing anyone any great injustice since my "interesting/professional" posts weren't happening anyway. So here's a summary of where I am right now:

My unemployment came to an end at the beginning of May. I am working at <a title="Viator" href="http://www.viator.com" target="_blank">Viator</a> doing many interesting things, and am very happy there. It's a large reason why I've been too busy to be online and to work on things like my website, or anything much in general. Between my full-time job with them, the side work I do for <a title="Gingery &amp; Associates" href="http://www.gingeryinfo.com" target="_blank">Gingery &amp; Associates</a>, and the <a title="Shining Stars Foundation" href="http://www.shiningstarsfoundation.org" target="_blank">Shining Stars Foundation</a>, plus commuting and trying to cram in actual eating/showering/cleaning house, my personal time has been minimal. I am not complaining about this fact. I much prefer how life is going right now to the alternative. I'm happy to be busy, productive, and gainfully employed. I'm learning how to balance a full-time job out of the house with a relationship and personal time. I am working out how to have more time for my hobbies in the future.

Speaking of hobbies I have started rehearsals for Sir Arthur Conan Doyle's The Speckled Band with the <a title="Orinda Starlight Village Players" href="http://www.orsvp.org" target="_blank">Orinda Starlight Village Players</a>. It's currently taking up all my weeknights but I'm happy to be doing theatre again. It has been a year and half since I last did a show, and 4 years since I last did a straight play. I chose to take time off from theatre to pursue other interests, such as night classes, networking, and developing a social life, but I can never stay away from the stage for long and hope to go back to performing on a regular basis again.

Currently I am on my 2nd ever vacation, which has been surreal and very welcome. It is also the reason that I have the time to write this post. I am in Ashland, Oregon for the Oregon Shakespeare Festival with my boyfriend and his family. It has been an incredible experience so far; I've seen 4 shows so far in the last few days, and have 3 more to see before we leave. I've never had the chance to see so much theatre in so short of a time, though I've always dreamed about going to New York City to do basically the same thing. I haven't taken as many pictures as I normally would on a trip to a place such as this; usually I'm so camera-happy, but I find myself just living in the moment and forgetting to record the experience. There is a freedom in that I'd say, and I suppose I've been more relaxed about documenting my life in general ever since I lost it all in the robbery.

Today though, life is good.]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[Talk about extreme neglect of my website. I never even finished my "year in review" that I do at the end of every year. Trying to do it as a blog this year instead of an electronic newsletter made it too long and overwhelming until I abandoned it completely. I've hardly been online these past few months, and while the reasons are mostly happy ones, I do wish I had more time for my side projects, such as this website. For a while I was trying to keep this blog less personal and more about things other people might be interested in, but I suppose that's what twitter is for and in the end this is my space to do with it what I will.]]></excerpt:encoded>

The funny thing is that I was listening to music on my iPhone as I was walking, and no joke, The Cat in the Hat from Seussical the Musical was the song playing when I saw this.</p>]]></content:encoded>

		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Tonight is unreal, and a reminder that once in a while I do catch a break. Sitting at the opera in seats I will never in my lifetime be able to afford, receiving a special backstage tour which was awe-inspiring, and being able to share it with a partner who loves both me and opera = about as good as it can get.</p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Thoughts on close friendships</title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2012/05/thoughts-on-close-friendships/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 03 May 2012 02:17:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2012/05/thoughts-on-close-friendships/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span>Last night I showed <em>Working</em> (the musical) to Jesse. It was the first time I&#8217;d watched it in a couple years and as I watched these people I used to know, I couldn&#8217;t help thinking, once again, about how sad it is that really close friendships can go away over night or you just get fed up eventually. Lately I&#8217;ve been thinking that if you get to know anyone well enough, that they&#8217;re bound to disappoint you at some point. I suppose that&#8217;s very pessimistic, but it&#8217;s been true in my life. It made me think, maybe everyone does bad things and if you don&#8217;t know the dark parts of someone, then things go along fine, but once you know the truth then it doesn&#8217;t work anymore.</span><br /><br /><span>I&#8217;m not trying to create an argument for not getting close to people. I often lament that fact that I am not closer to the people I&#8217;ve made friends with locally this past year. It&#8217;s just that most of the people I&#8217;ve been closest to in my life I have to stop communicating with, for some reason or another. Maybe I just become close with all the wrong kind of people, but I still think it&#8217;s more what I said before, that if you know anyone long enough, and well enough, they&#8217;re going to do things you don&#8217;t agree with, or they change too much, or they don&#8217;t change enough.</span><br /><br /><span>Maybe in the end, finding the right kinds of close friends is just as hard as finding the right kind of partner. I just know that the older I get, the harder it seems to try and make friends at all, so it&#8217;s especially disappointing when the long-term close ones fade away.</span></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title></title>
		<link>http://theamysloan.com/2012/05/sometimes-people-just-dont-get-how-blind-i-am/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 01 May 2012 03:09:45 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theamysloan.com/2012/05/sometimes-people-just-dont-get-how-blind-i-am/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[gallery]
<p>Sometimes people just don&#8217;t get how blind I am without my glasses on (or contacts), especially since it gets worse every year. If you&#8217;re more than a foot away from me, I cannot see your facial expressions. If I want to read something without my glasses on then I have to hold it right up to my face and close one eye. It&#8217;s something that scares me a lot, because I figure it&#8217;s only a matter of time before I go completely blind. I had a roommate who used to think it was funny to move my glasses when I was in the shower, or while I was sleeping and watch me frantically pat the ground and surroundings trying to find them.</p>
<p>I peeked out over my glasses earlier and thought sadly once again, &#8220;My eyes are getting worse,&#8221; and decided to try and replicate what it looks like. This is very hard to do since it isn&#8217;t just a matter of being blurry/fuzzy, but also some slight double vision as well, and the fuzziness can make some things pretty much disappear (and not just appear blurry). So this is my attempt to give you a look through my eyes, though this doesn&#8217;t mimic exactly what it is I see.</p>]]></content:encoded>
